  "description": "At 17, Warrant Officer Justin Thorn joined The Queen’s Own Rifles of Canada in June of 1988. During his 26 years in the Canadian Forces he has completed several taskings and exercises abroad, most notably in France, England, and the United States. Additionally, he has deployed twice domestically during the Ice Storms of January 1998, and during the Toronto winter deployment of January 1999. Warrant Officer Thorn has held several notable Regimental positions: section commander, platoon warrant, and Company Quartermaster. [&#8230;]",
  "content:encoded": "<p>At 17, Warrant Officer Justin Thorn joined <a title=\"The Queen’s Own Rifles of Canada\" href=\"http://www.qor.com/\" target=\"_blank\">The Queen’s Own Rifles of Canada</a> in June of 1988. During his 26 years in the<a title=\"Canadian Armed Forces\" href=\"http://www.forces.ca/en/home/\" target=\"_blank\"> Canadian Forces</a> he has completed several taskings and exercises abroad, most notably in <a title=\"France\" href=\"http://www.france.fr/en.html\" target=\"_blank\">France</a>, <a title=\"The United Kingdom\" href=\"https://www.gov.uk/\" target=\"_blank\">England</a>, and the <a title=\"United States of America\" href=\"http://www.usa.gov/\" target=\"_blank\">United States</a>. Additionally, he has deployed twice domestically during the <a title=\"Op recuperation\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/North_American_Ice_Storm_of_1998#Operation_Recuperation\" target=\"_blank\">Ice Storms</a> of January 1998, and during the <a title=\"1999 Toronto Snow Storm\" href=\"http://www.cbc.ca/archives/categories/environment/extreme-weather/extreme-weather-general/toronto-calls-in-troops-to-fight-massive-snowstorm.html\" target=\"_blank\">Toronto winter deployment of January 1999</a>.</p>\n<p>Warrant Officer Thorn has held several notable Regimental positions: section commander, platoon warrant, and Company Quartermaster. During his <a title=\"Class B Reserve Service\" href=\"http://publications.gc.ca/collections/Collection-R/LoPBdP/BP/prb9911-e.htm#1.%20Primarytxt\" target=\"_blank\">Class B</a> service from 1995 – 2002, he was the <a title=\"Canadian Armed Forces Recruiting\" href=\"http://www.forces.ca/en/home/\" target=\"_blank\">Recruiting</a> NCO and Regimental Quartermaster for 5 and 2 years respectively; this service earning him a Commanding Officer’s Commendation. He has also taught on numerous recruit, machine gun, driver-wheel and leadership courses.</p>\n<p>Currently Warrant Officer Thorn is the Company Sergeant Major of Buffs Company, The Queen’s Own Rifles of Canada. Of note is that The QOR is the only Reserve infantry <a title=\"Canadian Airborne Forces Collection\" href=\"http://www.petawawamuseums.ca/index.php/collections/cafcollection\" target=\"_blank\">airborne</a> unit in <a title=\"Canada\" href=\"http://canada.ca\" target=\"_blank\">Canada</a>; Warrant Thorn also serving in various capacities within the airborne contingent. Warrant Thorn completed his <a title=\"Canadian Basic Parachutist Course\" href=\"http://www.cg.cfpsa.ca/cg-pc/Petawawa/EN/FitnessandSports/MilitaryFitness/MilitaryFitnessTesting/Pages/PREPARA.aspx\" target=\"_blank\">Canadian Basic Parachutist Course</a> in August 1990. He obtained his <a title=\"Parachutist Badge (United Kingdom)\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parachutist_Badge_(United_Kingdom)\" target=\"_blank\">British jump wings</a> in 1992 and U.S. wings in 1994.</p>\n<p>Some of Warrant Officer Thorn’s significant military related memories are:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Marching The QOR’s 50 person guard onto Rue (road) de Queen’s Own Rifles in <a title=\"Bernieres-sur-Mer\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Berni%C3%A8res-sur-Mer\" target=\"_blank\">Bernieres-sur-Mer</a>, <a title=\"Normandy\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Normandy\" target=\"_blank\">Normandy</a>, <a title=\"France\" href=\"http://www.france.fr/en.html\" target=\"_blank\">France</a> on 6 June 1994 in celebration and remembrance of the Regiment’s <a title=\"D-Day\" href=\"http://www.veterans.gc.ca/eng/remembrance/history/second-world-war/d-day\" target=\"_blank\">D-Day</a> landing exactly 50 years earlier.</li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n<li>Being awarded the 2001 <a title=\"1st Canadian Parachute Battalion Association\" href=\"http://airborneassociation.com/e/media/oldnews/12D70/\" target=\"_blank\">1<sup>st</sup> Canadian Parachute Battalion Association</a>’s <a title=\"Reginald A. Walker Award\" href=\"http://qormuseum.org/history/awards/\" target=\"_blank\">Reginald A. Walker Award</a>, given to a QOR ‘Soldier who most exemplifies the spirit and physical fitness required’ of QOR members.</li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n<li>Being awarded top candidate on his Senior Leadership Course in 2002</li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n<li>In December 2005 &#8211; <a title=\"Canada’s Year of the Veteran\" href=\"http://canadaonline.about.com/od/canadaatwar/a/yearofveteran.htm\" target=\"_blank\">Canada’s Year of the Veteran</a> &#8211; having the opportunity to participate in several ceremonies commemorating the 60<sup>th</sup> anniversary of the release of Canadian Hong Kong Prisoners-of from War World War II. This included the humbling opportunity to escort several <a title=\"Hong Kong Veterans\" href=\"http://www.veterans.gc.ca/eng/remembrance/history/second-world-war/canadians-hong-kong\" target=\"_blank\">Hong Kong Veterans</a> at graveside ceremonies to pay respect and honour those who had fallen.</li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n<li>Being selected to, and subsequently meeting, the QOR’s Colonel-in-Chief, Her Royal Highness Camilla, <a title=\"The Duchess of Cornwall\" href=\"http://www.princeofwales.gov.uk/the-duchess-of-cornwall\" target=\"_blank\">Duchess of Cornwall </a>&#8211; current QOR Colonel-in-Chief &#8211; during a post-ceremony gathering in 2012.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Beyond his military career, Justin has a degree in Bachelor of Arts (Honours Political Science). Commencing in 2002, he joined the <a title=\"Peel Regional Police\" href=\"http://www.peelpolice.on.ca/en/\" target=\"_blank\">Peel Regional Police</a>. Warrant Officer Thorn has served in numerous capacities within Peel Police, including: uniform patrol, training officer, traffic enforcement, criminal investigation, neighbourhood policing and bike/cycling patrol duty, and as an Acting Sergeant. Additionally, he currently leads a <a title=\"Scouts Canada\" href=\"http://www.scouts.ca\" target=\"_blank\">Scouts Canada</a> Troop in <a title=\"City of Toronto\" href=\"http://www.toronto.ca\" target=\"_blank\">Toronto</a>; an organization that has seen him work with several Scouting sections during 35 years of membership, with 25 years of this service as a Scout leader.</p>\n<p>Follow me on Twitter @MikeLacroix32</p>\n<p>You can support this site by shopping on <a title=\"Amazon.ca\" href=\"http://www.amazon.ca?_encoding=UTF8&tag=thecanamilihi-20\" target=\"_blank\">Amazon</a>.  You still enjoy Amazon&#8217;s great prices, but a portion of your purchase goes to supporting the show.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<audio class=\"wp-audio-shortcode\" id=\"audio-748-26\" preload=\"none\" style=\"width: 100%;\" controls=\"controls\"><source type=\"audio/mpeg\" src=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/CMHP-Episode-033-WO-Justin-Thorn.mp3?_=26\" /><a href=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/CMHP-Episode-033-WO-Justin-Thorn.mp3\">http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/CMHP-Episode-033-WO-Justin-Thorn.mp3</a></audio>\n<p><a href=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Scan-4.jpeg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-753\" src=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Scan-4-300x205.jpeg\" alt=\"Scan 4\" width=\"300\" height=\"205\" srcset=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Scan-4-300x205.jpeg 300w, http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Scan-4-1024x701.jpeg 1024w, http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Scan-4.jpeg 1722w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px\" /></a></p>\n<p>Then Rfn Thorn immediately following his QL2 Basic graduation parade on the balcony of Moss Park Armoury, 1988</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Scan-3.jpeg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-752\" src=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Scan-3-300x199.jpeg\" alt=\"Scan 3\" width=\"300\" height=\"199\" srcset=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Scan-3-300x199.jpeg 300w, http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Scan-3-1024x682.jpeg 1024w, http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Scan-3.jpeg 1768w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px\" /></a></p>\n<p>Then Rfn Thorn on his QL4 Machine Gunner Course, Meaford, 1990.</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Scan-2.jpeg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-751\" src=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Scan-2-300x200.jpeg\" alt=\"Scan 2\" width=\"300\" height=\"200\" srcset=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Scan-2-300x200.jpeg 300w, http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Scan-2-1024x684.jpeg 1024w, http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Scan-2.jpeg 1766w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px\" /></a></p>\n<p>Then MCpl Thorn &#8216;on the advance&#8217;, Meaford, 1990s</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Scan.jpeg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-754\" src=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Scan-242x300.jpeg\" alt=\"Scan\" width=\"242\" height=\"300\" srcset=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Scan-242x300.jpeg 242w, http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Scan-828x1024.jpeg 828w, http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Scan.jpeg 870w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 242px) 100vw, 242px\" /></a></p>\n<div>Then Cpl Thorn with his father at a Regimental birthday weekend involving parachuting and rappelling demonstrations, c. 1993.</div>\n<div></div>\n<div>\n<p><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-750\" src=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Scan-1-195x300.jpeg\" alt=\"Scan 1\" width=\"195\" height=\"300\" srcset=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Scan-1-195x300.jpeg 195w, http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Scan-1-668x1024.jpeg 668w, http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Scan-1.jpeg 1153w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 195px) 100vw, 195px\" /></p>\n<p>Then Sgt Thorn during a summer field exercise in Petawawa, 1990s</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/jrtst4.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-757\" src=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/jrtst4-241x300.jpg\" alt=\"jrtst4\" width=\"241\" height=\"300\" srcset=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/jrtst4-241x300.jpg 241w, http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/jrtst4.jpg 597w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 241px) 100vw, 241px\" /></a></p>\n<p>Then Sgt Thorn with wearing a AN/PRC headset at the end of an evaluation exercise, c. 1999.</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Sab-Judy-JRT-2.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-749\" src=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Sab-Judy-JRT-2-225x300.jpg\" alt=\"Sab Judy JRT 2\" width=\"225\" height=\"300\" srcset=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Sab-Judy-JRT-2-225x300.jpg 225w, http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Sab-Judy-JRT-2.jpg 480w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 225px) 100vw, 225px\" /></a></p>\n<p>WO Thorn with friends.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n</div>\n<p><a href=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/1812-PM-CDS.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-756\" src=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/1812-PM-CDS-300x239.jpg\" alt=\"1812 PM CDS\" width=\"300\" height=\"239\" srcset=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/1812-PM-CDS-300x239.jpg 300w, http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/1812-PM-CDS.jpg 1024w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px\" /></a></p>\n<p>Members of The Queen&#8217;s Own Rifles of Canada including WO Thorn with The Prime Minister and the the CDS at a War of 1812 Reception at Fort York in Toronto</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/pMCgfpZhp9sz2EWafzh1kCLRMICxTBO7VPcpcbXGP3w.jpeg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-758\" src=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/pMCgfpZhp9sz2EWafzh1kCLRMICxTBO7VPcpcbXGP3w-300x300.jpeg\" alt=\"pMCgfpZhp9sz2EWafzh1kCLRMICxTBO7VPcpcbXGP3w\" width=\"300\" height=\"300\" srcset=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/pMCgfpZhp9sz2EWafzh1kCLRMICxTBO7VPcpcbXGP3w-300x300.jpeg 300w, http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/pMCgfpZhp9sz2EWafzh1kCLRMICxTBO7VPcpcbXGP3w-150x150.jpeg 150w, http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/pMCgfpZhp9sz2EWafzh1kCLRMICxTBO7VPcpcbXGP3w.jpeg 960w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px\" /></a></p>\n<p><a href=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/You-Outrank-Me-Now.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-755\" src=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/You-Outrank-Me-Now-300x264.jpg\" alt=\"You Outrank Me Now\" width=\"300\" height=\"264\" srcset=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/You-Outrank-Me-Now-300x264.jpg 300w, http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/You-Outrank-Me-Now-1024x902.jpg 1024w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px\" /></a></p>\n<p><a href=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/QGcE2LPq_6LikMpqBILyAjM.jpeg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-759\" src=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/QGcE2LPq_6LikMpqBILyAjM-300x225.jpeg\" alt=\"QGcE2LPq_6LikMpqBILyAjM\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" srcset=\"http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/QGcE2LPq_6LikMpqBILyAjM-300x225.jpeg 300w, http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/QGcE2LPq_6LikMpqBILyAjM-1024x768.jpeg 1024w, http://podcast.canadianmilitaryhistorypodcast.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/QGcE2LPq_6LikMpqBILyAjM.jpeg 1280w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px\" /></a></p>\n<p>The Queen&#8217;s Own Rifles of Canada tour Europe.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n",
